    "title": "Fault Path Integration",
    "objective": "Synthesize the roles of specific ADS conductors (CPC and Earthing Conductor) within a TN-C-S earthing arrangement.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a modern TN-C-S (PME) installation, the fault path relies on a specific sequence of conductors to ensure the protective device trips. A fault at an appliance first energizes the metal casing, then travels through the internal wiring of the building before reaching the supplier's equipment.",
      "Understanding the distinction between the conductor that serves the individual circuit and the conductor that serves the entire installation is vital for correct identification and testing."
    ],
    "questionText": "A fault occurs at a metal-clad socket in a building with a TN-C-S supply. Explain the path the fault current takes from the socket casing back to the supplier's cutout, specifically naming the two different green and yellow conductors it must pass through in the correct order.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The current travels from the socket casing through the CPC (Circuit Protective Conductor) to the MET (Main Earthing Terminal). From the MET, it travels through the Earthing Conductor to the supplier's cutout/PEN conductor in the TN-C-S system."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which conductor belongs to the 'circuit' and which one connects the 'whole installation' to the supplier's terminal."
  }
}

